@FerroTV @tomkeene I wanted to respectfully pushback from Jon Ferro's economic "green shoots" comment just now: Don't Buy Into 'The Broken Window Fallacy' * We are just fixing broken windows right now - not seeding future growth * It is my view that a lot of earnings capacity

is being removed from the economy by the virus and riots * A new Democratic Administration is highly likely - it will prioritize redistribution over growth * The markets are overextended and wholly dependent on the Fed stimulus and liquidity * However that stimuli - being

used to stabilize businesses/the economy, employees' incomes - is not likely to provide much of a catalyst for the future growth dynamic * That federal largesse has countered the Covid-19 economic shock by serving to weigh small businesses and large corporations with even more

debt - and that's a governor to growth * Meanwhile, paradigm shifts signal some permanence of job losses, a far slower than expected economic recovery and reduced economic potential and business "earnings power" @business

My 2020 @realdonaldtrump "No Apologies" Tour: June 11, 2020 The 1965 Voting Rights Act (VRA) required nine states to operate their voting laws under federal scrutiny because of their history of suppressing the vote among black Americans. In 2013, Chief Justice Roberts freed

those states—including Georgia—from federal oversight in his opinion, Shelby County v. Holder. In the key passage striking down the oversight provisions of the VRA, Roberts wrote: "Our country has changed. While any racial discrimination in voting is too much, Congress must

ensure that the legislation it passes to remedy that problem speaks to current conditions." Roberts was dissembling when he wrote that phrase in 2013. The country had not changed—and he knew it. The “current conditions” in Georgia are abysmal and sorely need federal oversight.

The voting debacle in black neighborhoods in this week’s Georgia primary is the result of either gross incompetence or malicious intent. Either way, the effect was to disenfranchise black voters—the very evil that the VRA was intended to prevent when Justice Roberts gutted

its provisions in 2013. With each passing hour, evidence mounts that the “malfunctions” that plagued the Georgia primary were suspiciously concentrated in black neighborhoods. See CNBC, “Georgia election 'catastrophe' in largely minority areas sparks investigation.”

(“Three-quarters of voters who called with problems identified as African American. In Roswell, a mostly white Atlanta suburb, there were far fewer problems.”) The Republican Secretary of State, who is responsible for running statewide elections, blamed local officials and

demanded an investigation of the election that he ran. Talk about chutzpah! As the nation begins to reckon with its pervasive racism, Republicans are fighting a rearguard action that denies the reality of endemic racism that is plain for all to see. The evident racial animus in

Georgia’s voter suppression efforts is a prime example. Even as the debacle unfolded, Trump’s chief economic advisor, Larry Kudlow, repeatedly denied on Wednesday that blacks faced systemic racism in America, as did Trump’s Press Secretary, Kayleigh McEnany. As protestors pull
